	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Noctoadal</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Hmm.<br />
<br />
I'm an attempting-to-quit-not-really-being-very-good-at-it smoker myself. Although, facts are facts, and (at least here, I don't see why it would be any different there,) smoking kills about half of those who do it. The costs to society in a monetary sense are astounding for all the care that patients with various smoking-related health problems require.<br />
<br />
Further, watching someone die of lung cancer is fucked up. Every breathe is a pain in the arse and causes them discomfort.<br />
<br />
Heroin will kill you in a night. That is undeniably tragic, however in terms of 'care', all they need is a jab from a paramedic (assuming they arrive on time) of adrenaline and Bob's your sister. Comparing this to the costs of, say, chemotherapy (thousands and thousands of dollars) for starters... well...</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
People die, every single one of them.  That dying is generally expensive and if you really want to be cut-throat about it, dying when you are 90 is generally much more 'expensive' to society than dying when you are 70.<br />
<br />
The whole concept that smokers are an unfair burden on health care hasn't been seriously used in accounting circles in quite a long time.  If anything, between extra taxes paid and being a lighter burden on pensions and such, they are a cheap category for nations that subsidize health care and provide old age security.  This isn't even new though, I recall my economics professor doing a work-up back in '89 or so.<br />
<br />
Again, this isn't saying that tobacco does not have social costs though.  I just personally wish government would be a bit more consistent about things.  You can't say on the one hand that tobacco is the most dangerous drug in the world and with the other hand receive huge revenues from it and also leave it as legal.  Criminalize smoking or shut up.  At the very least one could regulate nicotine levels or phase cigarette sales out over time.  I say &quot;one could&quot; knowing full well though that the lobby is too powerful realistically.  It's sad but likely true.
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
<tr>
