		<div id="post_message_1283582">
                  
                  To clarify, I meant more specifically that smoking-related illness (not necessarily death) is a large monetary burden.<br />
<br />
I do, however, agree with the remainder of your post. The Government here cops a lot of flak for their revenue-drawing escapades with respect to tobacco and tobacco product sales. It's rather obvious that demand for tobacco is largely inelastic.<br />
<br />
Tax revenue in Australia for customs and excise on tobacco amount to several billion annually.<br />
<br />
I often have this discussion with people: imagine the socially acceptable drug, alcohol, being discovered for the first time and being made by every-day people who sell it in an uncontrolled fashion. Here you'd see a drug that made people lose motor skills, slur speech, cause headaches, increase a tendency to be violent (both verbally and physically), crash their car, etc... that drug would be banned for sure.<br />
<br />
I don't think it's too outlandish an opinion, looking at tobacco and alcohol, that the Government <i>really would</i> allow it if it could be regulated for taxation purposes.
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
